There are multiple critical issues in the current EI report generation that must be clearly understood and addressed.

First, the highest priority issue is handling of direct Maximum Daily Intake (MDD) inputs. In some injection-type Excel inputs, the user directly provides component-level Maximum Daily Intake values (e.g., “Maximum Daily Intake (g)” per ingredient). In such cases, the system must still generate the report correctly. Currently, the system implicitly expects ratio-based or mg/mL-based inputs and can become inconsistent or confused when only MDD is provided. The key problem is that the pipeline is not consistently treating MDD as the final daily intake source when it is clearly present in the Excel, even though no further derivation is required.

Second, annexure mapping is unreliable. Based on the traceability Excel provided, multiple ingredients such as Egg Phospholipid (80% PC), Soybean oil (Purified, 700), Dehydrated Alcohol, Sodium Oleate B, and Sodium Hydroxide are marked as “No match” with zero confidence, even though corresponding annexures are present in the uploaded data. This indicates that the system is failing to resolve ingredient identity correctly between the composition table and annexure metadata. The problem is not annexure availability but incorrect or weak matching logic, leading to valid annexure data being ignored. As a result, the EI tables contain false zero concentrations and incomplete exposure values.

Third, page border rendering is broken. The generated document applies black page borders, but large tables exceed the content area and overflow into the header region or beyond the border. This results in visually broken output where tables are misaligned and extend outside the page boundary. This is purely a rendering/layout issue and is consistently degrading the quality of the final document.

Fourth, the generated content contains unnecessary aesthetic artifacts such as asterisks or special symbols that are not part of the scientific or regulatory content. These extra characters clutter the document and reduce professional quality. Only required scientific and regulatory text should be generated; no decorative or unnecessary symbols should appear.

Fifth, annexure naming is hallucinating. In the “List of annexures” section, especially for later annexures (e.g., Annexure 11 in the provided example), the system is generating long, irrelevant, and inconsistent names that do not correspond to any real uploaded annexure. This indicates that the system is not strictly using actual annexure metadata and is instead generating names heuristically or hallucinating them. This is a serious integrity issue because annexure naming must be exact and traceable to source documents.

Overall, the system currently has issues in correctly using direct MDD inputs, reliably mapping components to annexures even when data exists, maintaining clean and bounded document layout (especially with large tables and borders), avoiding unnecessary aesthetic artifacts, and ensuring that annexure names are strictly sourced from actual data without hallucination.
